[[File:Assyrianfolkdance.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|right|An [[Assyrian people|Assyrian]] dance party where participants engage in [[Assyrian folk dance|folk dancing]], [[Chicago]], USA.]]
A '''dance party''' (also referred to as a '''dance''') is a social gathering where [[dancing]] is the primary activity. Some dance parties are held in a casual setting and open to the public, such as a [[rave]], or those held in [[nightclub]]s and [[discothèque]]s. 

Other types of dance parties may be a formal or semi-formal private event which often require guests to don [[formal wear]] and have an invitation or membership within the community hosting the event, such as [[Dance party#School dances|school dance]]s and [[Cotillion ball|cotillions]]. 

Guests of formal dances often attend in pairs, as consorts or "dates" for one another. The term "stag" refers to going without a consort to a dance organized for couples.<ref>{{cite web|title=go stag - Idioms|url=http://idioms.thefreedictionary.com/go+stag|work=The Free Dictionary|publisher=Farlex|accessdate=30 September 2011}}</ref> Dances commonly take place during the evening, although some are held earlier during the daytime; such events are known as [[tea dance]]s.

==Casual dances==
Casual dances are dances that do not have a formal dress requirement; these may include school and community events, raves, evening entertainments provided for guests aboard a [[cruise ship]], and events organized for certain holidays, such as [[Halloween]] and [[Mardis Gras]].
[[File:Unga par på skoldans - Nordiska museet - NMA.0030481.jpg|thumb|Young couples at a school dance in 1950s [[Sweden]].]]

==School dances==
{{Redirect|School Dance|the 2014 film|School Dance (film)}}
{{Further|:Category:School dances}}
A school dance is a dance sponsored by a school, and may be [[Casual wear|casual]] or [[Formal wear|formal]]. Casual school dances were originally limited to Western countries, although schools in other countries{{where?|date=September 2011}} are beginning to adopt such events.{{As of?|date=May 2012}} There are some schools, such as [[Arlington High School (Massachusetts)|Arlington High School]] in [[Arlington, Massachusetts]], that prohibit school-hosted dances, citing sex and alcohol problems.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/30/arlington-high-school-ban_n_1121038.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Carolyn | last=Gregoire | title=Should Schools Ban Dances Because Of Grinding? | date=2011-11-30}}</ref>

===In the United States===
{{main|Prom}}
One of the most significant school dances is [[prom]], a relatively formal event normally reserved for [[Junior (education)#High school|Junior]] grade and [[Senior (education)#High school|Senior]] grade students. Some schools host a [[winter formal]], a similar event, for the lower grades. In the 1950s, informal school dances in the United States were often called [[sock hop]]s. The traditional [[Sadie Hawkins dance]] may be formal or semi-formal.

==Formal dances==
{{main|Ball (dance)}}
[[File:Vienna Ball in Moscow.jpg|thumb|Vienna Ball in [[Moscow]], Russia]]
[[File:Quadrille set five person set colonial ball at the Albert Hall.jpg|thumb|Historical Colonial Ball in the [[Albert Hall, Canberra|Albert Hall]] Canberra ( circa 2016) ([[sepia tone|sepia]])]]
One type of formal dance, known as a ball, is a dance event where guests [[formal wear|dress formally]]. In Western culture, a male may don [[white tie]] and a female may don a [[ball gown]]. Dinner dances are formal dances where dinner is served. Often, the style of music played at a ball is most suited to [[ballroom dancing]].

==Popularity==
{{globalize|section|date=September 2011}}
In Australia, dance parties are popular amongst [[teenagers]], to the point that many dance parties are held specifically for teenagers in [[nightclub]]s or other locations which allow [[underage]] guests, who are usually unable to attend such places due to [[local law]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consumer.vic.gov.au/CA256EB5000644CE/page/Listing-Liquor-Minors+on+licensed+premises?OpenDocument&1=75-Liquor~&2=0-Liquor~&3=~ |last=Lygopoulos |first=Anna |title=Minors on licensed premises |publisher=[[Consumer Affairs Victoria]] |date=2007-10-19 |accessdate=2009-01-18 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723154235/http://www.consumer.vic.gov.au/CA256EB5000644CE/page/Listing-Liquor-Minors+on+licensed+premises?OpenDocument&1=75-Liquor~&2=0-Liquor~&3=~ |archivedate=2008-07-23 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>

==Ambience==
[[File:Sensation White 08.03.2008 015.jpg|thumb|right|A rave held in a warehouse-sized venue, with elaborate lighting and powerful sound system.]]
Dance parties are usually held at night, and may be hosted in private homes, [[Bar (establishment)|bars]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.minus18.org.au/joomla/index.php?option=com_magazine&func=show_article&id=45 |title=September dance party |date=2008-08-04 |publisher=minus18.org.au |accessdate=2009-01-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081226134728/http://www.minus18.org.au/joomla/index.php?option=com_magazine&func=show_article&id=45 |archivedate=2008-12-26 |df= }}</ref> [[gymnasiums]], nightclubs, [[community center]]s, [[ballroom]]s, or other large open spaces suitable for use as a [[Performance surface|dance floor]] by many people simultaneously.

The music at dance parties is usually played through a [[public address|PA system]] or a more powerful [[Sound reinforcement system|sound system]], and is often supplied by a [[DJ]] who selects and plays pre-[[Sound recording and reproduction|recorded]] songs from [[vinyl record]]s, [[compact disc]]s or with a [[laptop]]; however, some dance parties feature live instrumentalists or musicians playing their music live on an instrument, or with a laptop. Raves and other large,{{quantify|date=September 2011}} modern dance parties use [[visual effects|visual]] and [[lighting|lighting effect]]s, such as [[strobe light]]ing and [[fog machine|smoke machines]].{{clear}}

==Cultural milestones==
In the Jewish community, [[Bar and Bat Mitzvah]] celebrations often involve dances.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705305033/Teen-party-disasters.html|title=Tips for avoiding teen party disasters|date=May 18, 2009|work=Deseret News|accessdate=16 November 2010|location=New York}}</ref>

Dances are common for [[Quinceañera]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latinamericanstudies.org/quince-1.htm|title=Quinceañera Festivity|last=de la Cova|first=Tony|date=November 30, 2008|accessdate=16 November 2010}}</ref> [[sweet sixteen (birthday)|sweet sixteen]] parties and [[débutante]] celebrations. Some of these [[coming of age]] events involve a [[father-daughter dance]].

At [[wedding reception]]s, the [[newlywed]] couple may opt to have a [[first dance]] (before all guests are invited to participate on the dance floor).

A dance party that is gaining popularity is the [[Bollywood]] dance party, featuring music from [[Hindi]] cinema from [[India]]. A popular dance party that demonstrates this style of music and dance combination is produced by Wicked Karma <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wicked-karma.com|title=Wicked Karma|last=Christie|first=Lo|date=June 1, 2013|accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref> that is produced by Christie Lo and DJ RDX <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.djrdxseattle.com|title=DJ RDX|last=Batra|first=Rohit|date=June 1, 2013|accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref>

Nurai, a nightclub in [[Beirut]] hosted a party event on the 28th August 2017 and by August 30th 2017 it broke the [[Guinness World Record]] for hosting a 56-hour long party to show that it is the best party city in the world!<ref>{{cite web|title=Lebanon Breaks Guinness World Record For Hosting The Longest Party In The World!|url=https://www.the961.com/lebanon-breaks-guinness-world-record-for-longest-party-in-the-world/|publisher=The 961|first=Grace|last=H|date=September 2, 2017|accessdate=September 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Beirut To Break The Record For World’s Longest Continuing Party At 56 Hours|url=https://stateofmind13.com/2017/08/15/beirut-to-break-the-record-for-worlds-longest-continuing-party-at-56-hours/|publisher=A Separate State of Mind|accessdate=September 4, 2017}}</ref>

==Specialized events==
Some dance events may put an emphasis on certain genres of dance. For example, an event may feature [[swing dance|swing]] or [[square dance|square dancing]] rather than dancing in general.  A [[masked ball]] is a type of [[costume party]] that features dancing. Dance parties at which people mainly dance [[Tango (dance)|Tango]] are called [[Milonga (place)|Milongas]].

